File: Eskom says its revenue application did not include any allocation for performance bonuses. JOHANNESBURG - Eskom is rubbishing Sunday newspaper reports that it applied for R1.8-billion to pay performance bonuses. The utility says its revenue application did not include any allocation for performance bonuses. READ: Eskom and economy a priority: Ramaphosa The application only includes a provision for a 13th cheque between 2019 and 2022. Eskom maintains that no performance bonuses have been paid to employees in the past two years. READ: Eskom's new CEO takes helm with power shake-up on agenda At the same time, the energy giant will lock horns with the regulator in court next week. This is over Nersa's decision to deduct R69-billion that government gave Eskom as shareholder support from the approved revenue budget.